ce:section.ce:para:
Photoanode samples were obtained via a multi-step synthesis method (Fig. 1
                        ). In the first step, FTO glasses were utilized as the substrate and TiO2 catalysts were grown on their surface to prepare the TiO2 NA sample. Then S, N-CDs were preliminarily modified on the TiO2 NA surface via a hydrothermal method and spliced to form the SNCL via a pyrolysis process. The top-down and cross-sectional (inset) SEM images of the TiO2 NA sample are shown in Fig. 2
                        a. The TiO2 catalyst was vertically grown on the FTO substrate with a thickness of 3.4 μm. The average diameter of a single TiO2 nanorod was approximately 20–40 nm. No obvious morphology change was observed in the SEM images after constructing the SNCL, for either the SNCL 0.25/TiO2 NA or SNCL 5/TiO2 NA sample (Fig. 2b and c). However, noticeable changes were observed in their TEM images. As shown in Fig. 2d–a rod structure with smooth surface was exhibited in TEM image of the pure TiO2 NA sample. The typical lattice fringes of 0.23 nm could be clearly observed, corresponding to (110) crystal plane of rutile TiO2 [33]. The TEM image of the SNCL 0.25/TiO2 NA is displayed in Fig. 2e. After being modified with S, N-CDs, the smooth surface of the TiO2 nanorods obviously roughened. Additionally, the extra lattice fringes were observed with different directions from those of the rutile TiO2. Their lattice spacing was counted as 0.21 nm and 0.32 nm, which corresponded to (100) and (002) planes of the graphitic carbon structure, respectively [29]. As the concentration of the S, N-CDs further increased, an extremely rough carbon layer structure eventually formed on the surface of the SNCL 5/TiO2 NA sample (Fig. 2f).
